<h3>The Question</h3>
<p>
    The <a href="/blocks/pagination/">pagination</a> a11y baseline is verified
    (<code>&lt;nav aria-label="pagination"&gt;</code> + <code>aria-current="page"</code>), but one behavior was
    deliberately left unverified by the pagination standard research report
    (<code>reports/2026-06-03-pagination-standard-research.md</code>):
    when the user moves to a new page, <strong>what happens to focus</strong> and <strong>what is
    announced</strong>? This survey runs the owed WAI-ARIA APG / NN-g / screen-reader-practice pass that grounds
    the open fork in <a href="/backlog/059-pagination-focus-announcement/">backlog&nbsp;#059</a> — and asks the
    prior question: is either half net-new vocabulary, or already-owned composition?
</p>

<h3>Recommendation (grounds #059)</h3>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Neither half is net-new.</strong> Focus after a page change <em>is</em> the focus-after-view-swap
        question, already owned by <a href="/intents/autofocus-on-activation/">Autofocus-on-Activation</a> (the
        <a href="/intents/navigation/">Navigation</a> intent already composes it for view swaps). The
        announcement <em>is</em> the clause-joined polite-status pattern already shipped by
        <a href="/blocks/data-table/">Data Table</a>, owned by
        <a href="/intents/live-region-status/">Live Region Status</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Focus → compose <code>autofocus-on-activation</code>.</strong> Default <code>heading</code> (the
        APG answer — focus the results region's heading); <code>preserve</code> is the rapid-paging opt-in (stay
        on the control); <code>auto</code> for a full-reload <code>?page=n</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Announcement → compose <code>live-region-status</code>, <code>urgency: polite</code>.</strong>
        Populate the one polite region with <em>"Page 2 of 10"</em> on every change — the same
        <code>announce()</code> shape Data Table uses. Mandatory, not a toggle.</li>
    <li><strong>Build = renderer wiring, not authoring.</strong> The pagination renderer already has the
        <code>role="status"</code> region; it is simply not populated on a page change, and focus is not moved.
        A thin block-author task — no new intent, no protocol.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Finding 1 — focus and announcement are two independent axes</h3>
<p>
    Every source treats them separately. Moving focus to a heading incidentally reads that heading, but the
    <a href="https://webaim.org/discussion/mail_thread?thread=9022">WebAIM thread</a> is explicit it is
    insufficient alone (<em>"screen readers will definitely need some information letting them know… the page
    was updated"</em>); and a live-region announcement moves no focus. So the trait model needs <strong>two</strong>
    dimensions, not one coupled "a11y" toggle — mirroring pagination's own presentation&nbsp;×&nbsp;protocol split.
</p>

<h3>Finding 2 — a page change IS a surface activation (grounds the focus fork)</h3>
<p>
    The WAI-ARIA APG answer to <em>"a new surface became active, where does focus land?"</em> is the results
    region's heading, made focusable (<code>tabindex="-1"</code> + <code>.focus()</code>). WE already extracted
    this as <a href="/intents/autofocus-on-activation/">Autofocus-on-Activation</a>, whose <code>landing</code>
    dimension is exactly <code>heading | target | preserve | auto</code>, default <code>heading</code>. The
    <a href="/intents/navigation/">Navigation</a> intent <em>already composes</em> this atom for view swaps. A
    <code>paged</code> page change is a view swap of the results region — so pagination composes the same atom.
    The four values map onto every option the sources debate:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong><code>heading</code> (default)</strong> — focus the results heading (<em>"Search results, page 2
        of 10"</em>); the APG answer and the option a screen-reader user in the WebAIM thread <em>"marginally
        prefer[s]… it lines me up for reading the new records."</em></li>
    <li><strong><code>target</code></strong> — an author-named element (e.g. the first result).</li>
    <li><strong><code>preserve</code></strong> — leave focus on the control; the rapid-paging preference
        (<em>"I might want to hit 'next page' several times"</em>) and the natural value for load-more.</li>
    <li><strong><code>auto</code></strong> — platform default for a full-document reload of <code>?page=n</code>,
        where the browser handles focus and no script runs.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Finding 3 — the announcement is the shipped clause-joined polite status (grounds the announce fork)</h3>
<p>
    The page-change announcement is the same mechanism the verified range-label is: <code>role="status"</code> +
    <code>aria-atomic="true"</code> — W3C technique <strong>ARIA22</strong>, <em>sufficient</em> for
    <strong>WCAG&nbsp;2.1 SC&nbsp;4.1.3 Status Messages (AA)</strong>. WE's prior art is concrete:
    <code>announce()</code> in <code>blocks/renderers/data-table/renderDataTable.ts</code> builds a clause-joined
    string (<em>"Sorted by Salary, descending; 3 of 6 shown"</em>) for one polite region, and its own doc comment
    names pagination's <em>"page 2 of 10"</em> as the analogue to share the <strong>pattern</strong> (region +
    clause string), not the wording. Home = <a href="/intents/live-region-status/">Live Region Status</a>,
    <code>urgency: polite</code> (a page change is advisory, never an <code>alert</code>).
</p>

<h3>Finding 4 — no industry consensus on focus-movement → make it a dimension, not a baked mechanic</h3>
<p>
    The WebAIM list is the canonical airing of this question and does <strong>not</strong> converge: focus-to-heading
    vs focus-stays-on-control, with the synthesis <em>"whichever you choose, as long as you do it accessibly and
    consistently, users get used to it."</em> Design systems split along a different seam —
    <a href="https://primer.style/product/components/pagination/accessibility/">GitHub Primer</a>:
    <em>"When Pagination reloads the page, there is no need for any focus management"</em> vs move focus
    <em>"for dynamic in-page updates."</em> Both focus branches are legitimate end-states, so per WE's
    "dimension only if both branches are legitimate" rule, focus-movement is <strong>configurable</strong> — and
    it already is, because it <em>is</em> <code>autofocus-on-activation.landing</code> (default <code>heading</code>,
    <code>preserve</code> the opt-in). <strong>Announcement, by contrast, has unanimous support — a fixed
    mechanic (always announce), not a toggle.</strong>
</p>

<h3>Finding 5 — this is composition, not new vocabulary (the load-bearing conclusion)</h3>
<p>
    The item's framing predates the intents that now own both halves. With
    <a href="/intents/autofocus-on-activation/">Autofocus-on-Activation</a> (owns <code>landing</code>) and
    <a href="/intents/live-region-status/">Live Region Status</a> (owns the polite region) both shipped, and
    <a href="/intents/navigation/">Navigation</a> already demonstrating the exact focus-after-swap composition,
    the pagination block has nothing to <em>author</em> — only to <em>compose and wire</em>. This is the same
    outcome <a href="/backlog/013-gap-6-focus-announcements/">gap-6 (#013)</a> reached for the general
    focus/announce concern: the pieces are owned; only specific compositions remain. #059 is the pagination-specific
    composition — adding zero intents and zero protocols.
</p>

<h3>Finding 6 — there is no native focus/announce-after-page-change</h3>
<p>
    A full-document reload of <code>?page=n</code> lets the browser handle focus natively (and a URL fragment can
    target a heading) — that is the <code>landing: auto</code> path. But the usable patterns (load-more,
    SPA-paged) update content <em>without</em> a reload, so the platform provides no automatic focus move or
    announcement for them; both must be scripted. There is no <code>&lt;paginate&gt;</code> element. So the
    behavior is necessarily an ARIA-composed wiring, degrading to the native reload path for server-rendered
    numbered pagination.
</p>

